{"repo": "hylang/hy", "pull_number": 2685, "instance_id": "hylang__hy-2685", "issue_numbers": [2684], "base_commit": "ae2968552ee332ac551973fc381458371dfeaa6f", "patch": "diff --git a/NEWS.rst b/NEWS.rst\nindex 8e985e806..3494ea8c7 100644\n--- a/NEWS.rst\n+++ b/NEWS.rst\n@@ -2,6 +2,16 @@\n \n Hy is `semantically versioned <https://semver.org/>`__ since 1.0.0.\n \n+Unreleased\n+======================================================================\n+\n+Supports Python 3.x \u2013 Python 3.y\n+\n+Bug Fixes\n+------------------------------\n+\n+* Captured exception variables are now properly scoped.\n+\n 1.2.0 (\"Crackers and Snacks\", released 2026-01-14)\n ======================================================================\n \ndiff --git a/hy/compiler.py b/hy/compiler.py\nindex f62519528..472fdf324 100755\n--- a/hy/compiler.py\n+++ b/hy/compiler.py\n@@ -379,9 +379,10 @@ def warn_on_core_shadow(self, name):\n                 RuntimeWarning\n             )\n \n-    def get_anon_var(self, base=\"_hy_anon_var\"):\n+    def get_anon_var(self, base=\"anon\", name=\"\"):\n         self.anon_var_count += 1\n-        return f\"{base}_{self.anon_var_count}\"\n+        name = name and \"_\" + name\n+        return f\"_hy_{base}{name}_{self.anon_var_count}\"\n \n     def compile_atom(self, atom):\n         # Compilation methods may mutate the atom, so copy it first.\ndiff --git a/hy/core/result_macros.py b/hy/core/result_macros.py\nindex 44f3dd772..c696f4090 100644\n--- a/hy/core/result_macros.py\n+++ b/hy/core/result_macros.py\n@@ -1476,7 +1476,7 @@ def compile_try_expression(compiler, expr, root, body, catchers, orelse, finalbo\n         # See: https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#the-try-statement\n         with compiler.scope.create(ScopeLet) as scope:\n             if name:\n-                scope.add(name, name)\n+                name = scope.add(name, compiler.get_anon_var(\"exc\", name))\n             ebody = compiler._compile_branch(ebody)\n         ebody += asty.Assign(catcher, targets=[return_var], value=ebody.force_expr)\n         ebody += ebody.expr_as_stmt()\ndiff --git a/hy/scoping.py b/hy/scoping.py\nindex a2df341b7..538d6f526 100644\n--- a/hy/scoping.py\n+++ b/hy/scoping.py\n@@ -271,7 +271,7 @@ def add(self, target, new_name=None):\n                 raise ValueError(\"binding target may not contain a dot\")\n             name = mangle(target)\n             if new_name is None:\n-                new_name = self.compiler.get_anon_var(f\"_hy_let_{name}\")\n+                new_name = self.compiler.get_anon_var(\"let\", name)\n             self.bindings[name] = new_name\n             if isinstance(target, Symbol):\n                 return Symbol(new_name).replace(target)\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/native_tests/let.hy b/tests/native_tests/let.hy\nindex 94f0b1122..f13d928f4 100644\n--- a/tests/native_tests/let.hy\n+++ b/tests/native_tests/let.hy\n@@ -154,7 +154,6 @@\n         ;; let bindings should work in except block\n         (assert (= bar 33))\n         ;; but exception bindings can shadow let bindings\n-        (assert (= (get (locals) \"foo\") foo))\n         (assert (isinstance foo Exception))))\n     ;; let binding did not get clobbered.\n     (assert (= foo 42))))\ndiff --git a/tests/native_tests/try.hy b/tests/native_tests/try.hy\nindex 9d490d820..9a93429dc 100644\n--- a/tests/native_tests/try.hy\n+++ b/tests/native_tests/try.hy\n@@ -205,3 +205,12 @@\n       (raise ValueError :from NameError)\n       (except [e [ValueError]] e))\n     __cause__)))))\n+\n+\n+(defn test-except-scope []\n+  ; https://github.com/hylang/hy/issues/2684\n+  (setv e (try\n+    (/ 1 0)\n+    (except [e ZeroDivisionError]\n+      e)))\n+  (assert (isinstance e ZeroDivisionError)))\n", "problem_statement": "Assigning `(try \u2026)` to a variable name used for an exception may fail\n```hy\n(setv e (try\n  (/ 1 0)\n  (except [e ZeroDivisionError]\n    e)))\n(print e)  ; NameError: name 'e' is not defined\n```\n\nThis compiles to:\n\n```python\ntry:\n    e = 1 / 0\nexcept ZeroDivisionError as e:\n    e = e\nprint(e)\n```\n\nWe're trying to assign to an outer ``e`` in the ``except`` block, but that doesn't work, of course. We probably need a temporary variable for this.\n\n@scauligi You may be interested in this, since it involves scoping.\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/63d4ccde72ddce48bd40fd8f1916b2aeb2994aaa", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/6af8fe320653f447c3eb4a80d216665c9b9616b5"], "created_at": "2026-02-23T06:18:07Z"}
{"repo": "hylang/hy", "pull_number": 2692, "instance_id": "hylang__hy-2692", "issue_numbers": [2691], "base_commit": "24d02d7b1a9ea8b4e54bebaa059b402dd540ec6c", "patch": "diff --git a/NEWS.rst b/NEWS.rst\nindex 3494ea8c7..6dc37cf56 100644\n--- a/NEWS.rst\n+++ b/NEWS.rst\n@@ -11,6 +11,8 @@ Bug Fixes\n ------------------------------\n \n * Captured exception variables are now properly scoped.\n+* Fixed bugs in `hy.model-patterns.whole` (and other combinators that\n+  use it, like `brackets`) in which tuples were not always produced.\n \n 1.2.0 (\"Crackers and Snacks\", released 2026-01-14)\n ======================================================================\ndiff --git a/README.rst b/README.rst\nindex 8f52cce9f..fc533cc85 100644\n--- a/README.rst\n+++ b/README.rst\n@@ -14,13 +14,9 @@ Hy\n \n Lisp and Python should love each other. Let's make it happen.\n \n-Hy is a Lisp dialect that's embedded in Python. Since Hy transforms its Lisp\n-code into Python abstract syntax tree (AST) objects, you have the whole\n-beautiful world of Python at your fingertips, in Lisp form.\n+Hy is a Lisp dialect that's embedded in Python. Since Hy transforms its Lisp code into Python abstract syntax tree (AST) objects, you have the whole beautiful world of Python at your fingertips, in Lisp form.\n \n-To install the latest release of Hy, just use the command ``pip3 install\n---user hy``. Then you can start an interactive read-eval-print loop (REPL) with\n-the command ``hy``, or run a Hy program with ``hy myprogram.hy``.\n+To install the latest release of Hy, just use the command ``pip3 install --user hy``. Then you can start an interactive read-eval-print loop (REPL) with the command ``hy``, or run a Hy program with ``hy myprogram.hy``.\n \n * `The Hy homepage <http://hylang.org>`__\n * `Try Hy with a web console <http://hylang.org/try-hy>`__\ndiff --git a/docs/macros.rst b/docs/macros.rst\nindex 921f87f09..f95c36153 100644\n--- a/docs/macros.rst\n+++ b/docs/macros.rst\n@@ -191,6 +191,14 @@ A less trivial, and more common, usage of reader macros is to call :func:`hy.HyR\n \n     #do-twice (print \"This line prints twice.\")\n \n+A special feature of reader macros, compared to regular macros, is that if they return ``None`` (not to be confused with ``'None``, a symbol that evaluates to ``None``), no model is produced, as if the reader-macro call wasn't there. ::\n+\n+    (defmacro regular-macro [])\n+    (defreader reader-macro)\n+\n+    (print [1 (regular-macro) 2])  ; => [1, None, 2]\n+    (print [1 #reader-macro 2])    ; => [1, 2]\n+\n Here's a moderately complex example of a reader macro that couldn't be implemented as a regular macro. It reads in a list of lists in which the inner lists are newline-separated, but newlines are allowed inside elements. ::\n \n     (defreader matrix\ndiff --git a/hy/core/result_macros.py b/hy/core/result_macros.py\nindex c696f4090..6b4dfce61 100644\n--- a/hy/core/result_macros.py\n+++ b/hy/core/result_macros.py\n@@ -74,7 +74,7 @@ def pvalue(root, wanted):\n \n def maybe_annotated(target):\n     return (\n-       pexpr(sym(\"annotate\") + target + FORM).named('`annotate` form') |\n+       pexpr(sym(\"annotate\"), target, FORM).named('`annotate` form') |\n        (target >> (lambda x: (x, None))))\n \n \n@@ -88,12 +88,10 @@ def dotted(name):\n def digest_type_params(compiler, tp):\n     \"Return a `type_params` attribute for `FunctionDef` etc.\"\n \n-    if tp:\n-        if not PY3_12:\n-            compiler._syntax_error(tp, \"`:tp` requires Python 3.12 or later\")\n-        tp, = tp\n-    elif not PY3_12:\n+    if not tp:\n         return {}\n+    if not PY3_12:\n+       compiler._syntax_error(tp, \"`:tp` requires Python 3.12 or later\")\n \n     return dict(type_params = [\n         asty.TypeVarTuple(x[1], name = mangle(x[1]))\n@@ -103,7 +101,7 @@ def digest_type_params(compiler, tp):\n         asty.TypeVar(x[0],\n                name = mangle(x[0]),\n                bound = x[1] and compiler.compile(x[1]).force_expr)\n-        for x in (tp or [])])\n+        for x in tp[0]])\n \n \n # ------------------------------------------------\n@@ -1834,7 +1832,7 @@ def compile_class_expression(compiler, expr, root, decorators, tp, name, rest):\n # ------------------------------------------------\n \n module_name_pattern = SYM | pexpr(\n-    some(lambda x: isinstance(x, Symbol) and not str(x[0]).strip(\".\")) + oneplus(SYM)\n+    some(lambda x: isinstance(x, Symbol) and not str(x[0]).strip(\".\")), oneplus(SYM)\n )\n \n \ndiff --git a/hy/model_patterns.py b/hy/model_patterns.py\nindex 2497dbcaa..8518d4994 100644\n--- a/hy/model_patterns.py\n+++ b/hy/model_patterns.py\n@@ -15,6 +15,7 @@\n     many,\n     skip,\n     some,\n+    _IgnoredParser\n )\n \n from hy.models import (\n@@ -60,12 +61,21 @@ def _sym(wanted, f=lambda x: x):\n \n def whole(parsers):\n     \"\"\"Match the parsers in the given list one after another, then\n-    expect the end of the input.\"\"\"\n+    expect the end of the input. The result is always a tuple.\"\"\"\n     if len(parsers) == 0:\n-        return finished >> (lambda x: [])\n+        return finished >> (lambda _: ())\n+    non_ignored_parsers = sum(\n+        not isinstance(p, _IgnoredParser)\n+        for p in parsers)\n     if len(parsers) == 1:\n-        return parsers[0] + finished >> (lambda x: x[:-1])\n-    return reduce(add, parsers) + skip(finished)\n+        return ((parsers[0] >> (lambda r: (r,) if non_ignored_parsers else ())) +\n+            skip(finished))\n+    return ((\n+        reduce(add, parsers) >> (lambda r:\n+            () if non_ignored_parsers == 0 else\n+            (r,) if non_ignored_parsers == 1 else\n+            r)) +\n+        skip(finished))\n \n \n def _grouped(group_type, syntax_example, name, parsers):\n@@ -94,7 +104,7 @@ def pexpr(*parsers, name = None):\n def dolike(head):\n     \"\"\"Parse a :hy:func:`do`-like expression. ``head`` is a string used to\n     construct a symbol for the head.\"\"\"\n-    return pexpr(sym(head), many(FORM))\n+    return pexpr(sym(head), many(FORM)) >> (lambda r: r[0])\n \n \n def notpexpr(*disallowed_heads):\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/tests.yaml b/.github/workflows/tests.yaml\nindex e1a1692cc..54b7ffee9 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/tests.yaml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/tests.yaml\n@@ -56,8 +56,8 @@ jobs:\n     runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n \n     steps:\n-    - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n-    - uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n+    - uses: actions/checkout@v6\n+    - uses: actions/setup-python@v6\n       with: {python-version: 3}\n     - name: Install\n       run: |\ndiff --git a/tests/native_tests/model_patterns.hy b/tests/native_tests/model_patterns.hy\nindex 8aa5e6ee7..2d55c2b85 100644\n--- a/tests/native_tests/model_patterns.hy\n+++ b/tests/native_tests/model_patterns.hy\n@@ -66,3 +66,26 @@\n      for p in [k n (* 10 n)]\n      do (.append l p) (-= k 1))\n   (assert (= l [2 1 10  -1 2 20  -4 3 30])))\n+\n+(defn test-whole-with-skip []\n+  ; https://github.com/hylang/hy/issues/2691\n+\n+  (import\n+    hy.model-patterns [whole  FORM :as X]\n+    funcparserlib.parser [skip])\n+\n+  (assert (= (.parse (whole []) []) #()))\n+\n+  (assert (= (.parse (whole [X])        ['1]) #('1)))\n+  (assert (= (.parse (whole [(skip X)]) ['1]) #()))\n+\n+  (defn f [#* parsers]\n+    (.parse\n+       (whole parsers)\n+       ['1 '2 '3]))\n+\n+  (assert (= (f X        X         X)       #('1 '2 '3)))\n+  (assert (= (f (skip X) X         X)       #('2 '3)))\n+  (assert (= (f (skip X) (skip X)  X)       #('3)))\n+  (assert (= (f (skip X) X        (skip X)) #('2)))\n+  (assert (= (f (skip X) (skip X) (skip X)) #())))\ndiff --git a/tests/native_tests/reader_macros.hy b/tests/native_tests/reader_macros.hy\nindex 20e0e70dc..3b9c867fb 100644\n--- a/tests/native_tests/reader_macros.hy\n+++ b/tests/native_tests/reader_macros.hy\n@@ -50,6 +50,14 @@\n     (eval-isolated (next it) module)\n     (assert (= (next it) '\"hello, world!\"))))\n \n+(defn test-returning-none []\n+  (assert (=\n+    (eval-module #[[(defreader foo None) #(1 #foo 2)]])\n+    #(1 2)))\n+  (assert (=\n+    (eval-module #[[(defreader foo 'None) #(1 #foo 2)]])\n+    #(1 None 2))))\n+\n (defn test-bad-reader-macro-name []\n   (with [(pytest.raises HyMacroExpansionError)]\n     (eval-module \"(defreader :a-key '1)\"))\n", "problem_statement": "`whole` with `skip` doesn't always return a tuple\nOriginally reported by @KevinMGranger in #2688. \n\n```hy\n(import\n  hy.model-patterns [whole  FORM :as X]\n  funcparserlib.parser [skip])\n\n(defn f [#* parsers]\n  (.parse\n     (whole parsers)\n     ['1 '2 '3]))\n\n(print (f X        X         X))\n  ; (hy.models.Integer(1), hy.models.Integer(2), hy.models.Integer(3))\n(print (f (skip X) X         X))\n  ; (hy.models.Integer(2), hy.models.Integer(3))\n(print (f (skip X) (skip X)  X))\n  ; hy.models.Integer(3)\n(print (f (skip X) X        (skip X)))\n  ; hy.models.Integer(2)\n(print (f (skip X) (skip X) (skip X)))\n  ; _Ignored(None)\n```\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/01e9b2f6af0cf3b2660b2b246b96a34f87163e83", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/646218dfcf071e321b67ce123e7e7418d7b47cc5", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/7494806f6fc08c9622a0a80f6f7131746c859d6d", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/1686962cd890440ada0b981fadeb6f09d2eee38c", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/5ab218cb47a3919211fdb7b86ce753217a40066b"], "created_at": "2026-03-18T13:37:09Z"}
{"repo": "hylang/hy", "pull_number": 2699, "instance_id": "hylang__hy-2699", "issue_numbers": [2694], "base_commit": "9345e38cd6f51e8bf8b61dec3985b63ed79d2694", "patch": "diff --git a/AUTHORS b/AUTHORS\nindex 62c20acbf..9aa1a29ce 100644\n--- a/AUTHORS\n+++ b/AUTHORS\n@@ -111,3 +111,4 @@\n * Daniel Tan <danieltanfh95@gmail.com>\n * Zhan Tang <tz59pk@gmail.com>\n * Ati Sharma <ati@agalmic.ltd>\n+* Kevin M Granger <py@kmg.fyi>\ndiff --git a/NEWS.rst b/NEWS.rst\nindex 6dc37cf56..ec80e3ce0 100644\n--- a/NEWS.rst\n+++ b/NEWS.rst\n@@ -13,6 +13,8 @@ Bug Fixes\n * Captured exception variables are now properly scoped.\n * Fixed bugs in `hy.model-patterns.whole` (and other combinators that\n   use it, like `brackets`) in which tuples were not always produced.\n+* Added pattern matching support to String, Bytes, Symbol, Integer, Float,\n+  and Complex models.\n \n 1.2.0 (\"Crackers and Snacks\", released 2026-01-14)\n ======================================================================\ndiff --git a/hy/models.py b/hy/models.py\nindex cdce91af0..415e9676b 100644\n--- a/hy/models.py\n+++ b/hy/models.py\n@@ -149,6 +149,8 @@ class String(Object, str):\n       ``#[[hello]]`` is the empty string.\n     \"\"\"\n \n+    __match_args__ = (\"_as_str\",)\n+\n     def __new__(cls, s=None, brackets=None):\n         value = super().__new__(cls, s)\n         if brackets is not None and f\"]{brackets}]\" in value:\n@@ -165,6 +167,10 @@ def __repr__(self):\n     def __add__(self, other):\n         return self.__class__(super().__add__(other))\n \n+    @property\n+    def _as_str(self):\n+        return str(self)\n+\n \n _wrappers[str] = String\n \n@@ -174,7 +180,11 @@ class Bytes(Object, bytes):\n     Represents a literal bytestring (:class:`bytes`).\n     \"\"\"\n \n-    pass\n+    __match_args__ = (\"_as_bytes\",)\n+\n+    @property\n+    def _as_bytes(self):\n+        return bytes(self)\n \n \n _wrappers[bytes] = Bytes\n@@ -188,6 +198,8 @@ class Symbol(Object, str):\n     :func:`len`, and :class:`bool`; in particular, ``(bool (hy.models.Symbol \"False\"))`` is true. Use :hy:func:`hy.eval` to evaluate a symbol.\n     \"\"\"\n \n+    __match_args__ = (\"_as_str\",)\n+\n     def __new__(cls, s, from_parser=False):\n         s = str(s)\n         if not from_parser:\n@@ -201,6 +213,10 @@ def __new__(cls, s, from_parser=False):\n             return sym\n         return super().__new__(cls, s)\n \n+    @property\n+    def _as_str(self):\n+        return str(self)\n+\n \n _wrappers[bool] = lambda x: Symbol(\"True\") if x else Symbol(\"False\")\n _wrappers[type(None)] = lambda _: Symbol(\"None\")\n@@ -300,6 +316,8 @@ class Integer(Object, int):\n     Represents a literal integer (:class:`int`).\n     \"\"\"\n \n+    __match_args__ = (\"_as_int\",)\n+\n     def __new__(cls, number, *args, **kwargs):\n         return super().__new__(\n             cls,\n@@ -315,6 +333,10 @@ def __new__(cls, number, *args, **kwargs):\n             ),\n         )\n \n+    @property\n+    def _as_int(self):\n+        return int(self)\n+\n \n _wrappers[int] = Integer\n \n@@ -331,12 +353,17 @@ class Float(Object, float):\n     \"\"\"\n     Represents a literal floating-point real number (:class:`float`).\n     \"\"\"\n+    __match_args__ = (\"_as_float\",)\n \n     def __new__(cls, num, *args, **kwargs):\n         value = super().__new__(cls, strip_digit_separators(num))\n         check_inf_nan_cap(num, value)\n         return value\n \n+    @property\n+    def _as_float(self):\n+        return float(self)\n+\n \n _wrappers[float] = Float\n \n@@ -348,6 +375,7 @@ class Complex(Object, complex):\n     added to the imaginary part of the new model, but ``imag``, if provided, must be\n     real.\n     \"\"\"\n+    __match_args__ = (\"real\", \"imag\")\n \n     def __new__(cls, real, imag=0, *args, **kwargs):\n         if isinstance(real, str):\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/native_tests/match.hy b/tests/native_tests/match.hy\nindex 2ae2a3575..110727f1b 100644\n--- a/tests/native_tests/match.hy\n+++ b/tests/native_tests/match.hy\n@@ -128,7 +128,19 @@\n   ;; :as clause cannot come after :if guard\n   (with [(pytest.raises HySyntaxError)]\n     (hy.eval '(match 1\n-                     1 :if True :as x x))))\n+                     1 :if True :as x x)))\n+\n+  (defmacro assert-model-match [subject pattern]\n+     `(assert (match (quote ~subject) ~pattern True _ False)))\n+\n+  (assert-model-match \"foo\" (hy.models.String \"foo\"))\n+  (assert-model-match b\"1\" (hy.models.Bytes b\"1\"))\n+  (assert-model-match foo (hy.models.Symbol \"foo\"))\n+  (assert-model-match :foo (hy.models.Keyword \"foo\"))\n+  (assert-model-match 1 (hy.models.Integer 1))\n+  (assert-model-match 1.0 (hy.models.Float 1.0))\n+  (assert-model-match 1+2j (hy.models.Complex 1 2)))\n+\n \n (defn test-dotted-constructor []\n   ; https://github.com/hylang/hy/issues/2404\n", "problem_statement": "Cannot use `match` with models that inherit from certain builtins\n(I have confirmed this on 3.14 and for certain built-in types, I haven't tried other versions/types yet.)\n\n[Python's `match` spec for class patterns](https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#class-patterns) has an interesting edge case:\n\nIf a class singly-inherits from the list of builtins mentioned in the above link, then you can pattern-match with a single positional arg as the only class pattern.\n\n```python\nclass DirectChild(str):\n    pass\n\nclass DirectChildChild(DirectChild):\n    pass\n\nmatch DirectChildChild(\"foo\"):\n    case DirectChildChild(\"foo\"):\n        assert True\n    case other:\n        print(f\"no matches for {other!r}\")\n        assert False\n```\n\nHowever, as soon as you also inherit from another class, such as with `hy.models.String`/`Integer`/etc, it requires standard `__match_args__` behavior.\n\n```python\nimport hy.models as hm\n\nmatch hm.String(\"foo\"):\n    case hm.String(\"foo\"):\n        print(\"matched hm string foo?\")\n        assert False\n    case \"foo\":\n        print(\"matched string literal?\")\n        assert False\n    case other:\n        print(f\"no matches for {other!r}\")\n        assert True\n```\n\nThis can be accomplished one of two ways:\n1. Put the primitive type first in the inheritance (e.g. `class String(str, Object)`).\n2. With a property or attr that'll return an instance of the builtin type, and naming that in `__match_args__`:\n\n```python\nclass Base:\n    pass\n\nclass Str(Base, str):\n    __match_args__ = (\"_as_str\",)\n\n    @property\n    def _as_str(self):\n        return str(self)\n\n    # OR\n\n    def __new__(cls, s):\n        s = str(s)\n        value = super().__new__(cls, s)\n        value._as_str = s\n        return value\n\nmatch Str(\"foo\"):\n    case Str(\"foo\"):\n        print(\"matched Str foo\")\n        assert True\n    case other:\n        print(f\"no matches for {other!r}\")\n        assert False\n```\n\nI'd be happy to make a PR for this.\n\nI know one can get the desired behavior with model patterns, but if one's making tools for hy in python, this has less ceremony for the simple cases.\n\n_Note: it'd be nice to use a dunder method to hide the implementation detail (e.g. `__as_str`), but that won't work because of python name mangling._\n\n_Another note: this doesn't happen with the `hy.models.Sequence` subclasses for some reason, despite `tuple` also being in the list in the link. I don't why._\n", "hints_text": "Got overexcited and implemented it here: https://github.com/hylang/hy/compare/master...KevinMGranger:hy:matchable-models\n\nI made the fields attributes when there was already a __new__, and properties otherwise. Let me know if you want me to open the PR or make any changes.\nI see your point, but I think that changing this would be a breaking change, and I'm loath to go to Hy 2.0.0 for something like this. I think that Python's `match` was a bit ill-conceived, and users want something like a switch statement much more often than pattern-matching, so they'll be happier with Hyrule's more flexible and simpler `branch` and `case` than the built-in `match`.\nMatching against constant models would still be a pain even with this change because with all the restrictions on Python match patterns, you can't use `quote`: `(match '\"foo\"  '\"foo\" 1)` raises `NameError: name 'quote' is not defined`.\nMaking the builtins come first in the inheritance order might be a breaking change in ways we can't anticipate. But I don't quite see how the match args solution would break things?\n\nI think most lispers or those from functional backgrounds are disappointed with `match`, yes, and Hyrule has some alternatives that might fit better. But I'm focused on this for two reasons:\n\n1. I'm working on a Hy HTML generating / templating library that transforms models into properly escaped text. The core of it is in Python, because I want type checking feedback instantly, especially when making a mistake there could be a security issue.\n\n2. I think Hy is a great way to get Pythonistas into lisp. I know it's the first lisp that's really stuck with me, personally. And I think that they should interoperate as closely as possible.\n\nIf making the models matchable on the Python side while the macro doesn't support literals like that, making the Hy side almost seem second-class to the Python side, then I completely understand that. And I'd volunteer to help work on the match macro until it can support it.\n> But I don't quite see how the match args solution would break things?\n\nLet's look into this more closely, then. I don't think that it's true that \"as soon as you also inherit from another class, such as with `hy.models.String`/`Integer`/etc, it requires standard `__match_args__` behavior\". For example:\n\n```python\nclass B: pass\n\nclass C(str, B):\n   def __init__(self, a):\n       self.a = a\n   def __eq__(self, other):\n       return self.a == other\n\nmatch C(\"foo\"):\n    case C(\"foo\"):\n        print('works')\n```\n\nThe reason `String(\"foo\")` doesn't match against `String(\"foo\")` is that this checks `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"`, which fails because Hy models are by design not equal to non-models. This behavior is counterintuitive, and not useful because it means that pattern-matching against a model always fails, but it does arise naturally from Python's semantics and Hy's documented intentional behavior, so would changing this really be a bug fix, or a breaking change? We can't gate the change with a pragma because pragmata are lexically scoped and the methods called in a class can't see the lexical scope.\n\n@scauligi Thoughs?\nHmm, let me make clearer what I want. It is my philosophy that for most python objects, if two instances made with the same literals equal each other, then it should pattern match against the same expression that created it. And I also completely agree that a model should not equal the equivalent runtime value. Ceci n'est pas une pipe, non?\n\n| Current Behavior                                        | Desired       | Notes                                                                           |\n| ------------------------------------------------------- | ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| `assert String(\"foo\") != \"foo\"`, etc.                   | Keep          | A model is the not the same as the runtime value, yes!  |\n| `match String(\"foo\"): case \"foo\": assert False`         | Keep          | See above.                                                                      |\n| `assert String(\"foo\") == String(\"foo\")`                 | Keep          | If it's not `NaN`, the law of equality should hold.                             |\n| `match String(\"foo\"): case String(\"foo\"): assert False` | `assert True` | It's weird if matching constants isn't the same as equality checking, no?       |\n\n\nWhen inheriting from the primitive first, python will use the primitive pattern-matching behavior. That means that it will run `subject.__eq__($STRING_LITERAL)`, which'll catch `str.__eq__` from the MRO before `Object.__eq__`, so we wind up with `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"`.\n\nIf we use the `__match_args__` technique, then it would pattern match while still keeping `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"` behavior.\n\n<details>\n<summary> Unfold for a comparison of primitive-first-inheritance versus __match_args__ </summary>\n\n```python\nclass Object:\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        print(f\"Object.__eq__ {type(self)}: {self=!r}, {type(other)}: {other=!r}\")\n        return type(self) is type(other) and super().__eq__(other)\n\nclass StringStrFirst(str, Object): pass\n\nclass StringMatchArgs(Object, str):\n    __match_args__ = (\"_as_str\",)\n    def __new__(cls, s):\n        self = super().__new__(cls, s)\n        self._as_str = str(self)\n        return self\n\ndef matches_str_first(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case StringStrFirst(\"foo\"):\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\ndef matches_match_args(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"):\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\ndef matches_str(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case \"foo\":\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\n\nassert matches_str_first(StringStrFirst(\"foo\"))\n# do not want :(\nassert matches_str(StringStrFirst(\"foo\"))\n\nassert matches_match_args(StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"))\n# yay!\nassert not matches_str(StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"))\n```\n</details>\n\nI believe the only code that would break would be people who depended on having models not match themselves, which... well, [someone's always going to use emacs as a space heater](https://xkcd.com/1172/).\n@Kodiologist I view `(match (String \"foo\") (String \"foo\") 'pass  _ 'fail)` as a bug, so I agree with @KevinMGranger that this is a bugfix rather than a breaking change. I would find it highly surprising if anyone were relying on the current behavior, even if unintentionally.\n\n@KevinMGranger I suggest using the property-based accessor rather than setting a field, to minimize the chance of any sort of de-sync happening.\n\n---\n\nAnyhoodle, the reason why the various examples in this issue do/n't work is that `str` (and the other bulit-in types listed in the `match` docs) can be thought of as having something like `__match_args__ = ('(self)',)` (not actually a valid `__match_args__` but it gives the gist).\n\nSince `String` inherits from `str`, it also inherits this same behavior. When doing a case comparison then, Python compares the switch object's match fields to the tuple of args from the case pattern. For `String`, that effectively becomes `(String(\"foo\").(self),) == (\"foo\")`, which is why it fails.\n\n@Kodiologist's `class C` has a quirky definition of `__eq__` that ends up making the match cases work (it's comparing a field access on the left-hand side to the entire object on the right). Since `C` inherits the `str` class's \"compare self\" behavior, the match case is comparing `C(\"foo\")` itself vs the first subpattern `\"foo\"` from the case statement.\n```\nC(\"foo\") ==? \"foo\"\n=> C(\"foo\").a ==? \"foo\"\n=> \"foo\" == \"foo\"\n```\nHowever, if the `__eq__` method is changed to a more standard implementation\n```\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    return isinstance(other, C) and self.a == other.a\n```\nthen the match cases fail, since (correctly) `C(\"foo\") != \"foo\"`.\nOkay, let's change this and advertise it as a bug fix. @KevinMGranger Create a pull request at your leisure.\n> I suggest using the property-based accessor rather than setting a field, to minimize the chance of any sort of de-sync happening.\n\n@scauligi what do you mean by \"de-sync\"? As in the field gets out of sync with the instance?\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Got overexcited and implemented it here: https://github.com/hylang/hy/compare/master...KevinMGranger:hy:matchable-models\n\nI made the fields attributes when there was already a __new__, and properties otherwise. Let me know if you want me to open the PR or make any changes.\nI see your point, but I think that changing this would be a breaking change, and I'm loath to go to Hy 2.0.0 for something like this. I think that Python's `match` was a bit ill-conceived, and users want something like a switch statement much more often than pattern-matching, so they'll be happier with Hyrule's more flexible and simpler `branch` and `case` than the built-in `match`.\nMatching against constant models would still be a pain even with this change because with all the restrictions on Python match patterns, you can't use `quote`: `(match '\"foo\"  '\"foo\" 1)` raises `NameError: name 'quote' is not defined`.\nMaking the builtins come first in the inheritance order might be a breaking change in ways we can't anticipate. But I don't quite see how the match args solution would break things?\n\nI think most lispers or those from functional backgrounds are disappointed with `match`, yes, and Hyrule has some alternatives that might fit better. But I'm focused on this for two reasons:\n\n1. I'm working on a Hy HTML generating / templating library that transforms models into properly escaped text. The core of it is in Python, because I want type checking feedback instantly, especially when making a mistake there could be a security issue.\n\n2. I think Hy is a great way to get Pythonistas into lisp. I know it's the first lisp that's really stuck with me, personally. And I think that they should interoperate as closely as possible.\n\nIf making the models matchable on the Python side while the macro doesn't support literals like that, making the Hy side almost seem second-class to the Python side, then I completely understand that. And I'd volunteer to help work on the match macro until it can support it.\n> But I don't quite see how the match args solution would break things?\n\nLet's look into this more closely, then. I don't think that it's true that \"as soon as you also inherit from another class, such as with `hy.models.String`/`Integer`/etc, it requires standard `__match_args__` behavior\". For example:\n\n```python\nclass B: pass\n\nclass C(str, B):\n   def __init__(self, a):\n       self.a = a\n   def __eq__(self, other):\n       return self.a == other\n\nmatch C(\"foo\"):\n    case C(\"foo\"):\n        print('works')\n```\n\nThe reason `String(\"foo\")` doesn't match against `String(\"foo\")` is that this checks `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"`, which fails because Hy models are by design not equal to non-models. This behavior is counterintuitive, and not useful because it means that pattern-matching against a model always fails, but it does arise naturally from Python's semantics and Hy's documented intentional behavior, so would changing this really be a bug fix, or a breaking change? We can't gate the change with a pragma because pragmata are lexically scoped and the methods called in a class can't see the lexical scope.\n\n@scauligi Thoughs?\nHmm, let me make clearer what I want. It is my philosophy that for most python objects, if two instances made with the same literals equal each other, then it should pattern match against the same expression that created it. And I also completely agree that a model should not equal the equivalent runtime value. Ceci n'est pas une pipe, non?\n\n| Current Behavior                                        | Desired       | Notes                                                                           |\n| ------------------------------------------------------- | ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| `assert String(\"foo\") != \"foo\"`, etc.                   | Keep          | A model is the not the same as the runtime value, yes!  |\n| `match String(\"foo\"): case \"foo\": assert False`         | Keep          | See above.                                                                      |\n| `assert String(\"foo\") == String(\"foo\")`                 | Keep          | If it's not `NaN`, the law of equality should hold.                             |\n| `match String(\"foo\"): case String(\"foo\"): assert False` | `assert True` | It's weird if matching constants isn't the same as equality checking, no?       |\n\n\nWhen inheriting from the primitive first, python will use the primitive pattern-matching behavior. That means that it will run `subject.__eq__($STRING_LITERAL)`, which'll catch `str.__eq__` from the MRO before `Object.__eq__`, so we wind up with `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"`.\n\nIf we use the `__match_args__` technique, then it would pattern match while still keeping `String(\"foo\") == \"foo\"` behavior.\n\n<details>\n<summary> Unfold for a comparison of primitive-first-inheritance versus __match_args__ </summary>\n\n```python\nclass Object:\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        print(f\"Object.__eq__ {type(self)}: {self=!r}, {type(other)}: {other=!r}\")\n        return type(self) is type(other) and super().__eq__(other)\n\nclass StringStrFirst(str, Object): pass\n\nclass StringMatchArgs(Object, str):\n    __match_args__ = (\"_as_str\",)\n    def __new__(cls, s):\n        self = super().__new__(cls, s)\n        self._as_str = str(self)\n        return self\n\ndef matches_str_first(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case StringStrFirst(\"foo\"):\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\ndef matches_match_args(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"):\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\ndef matches_str(subject):\n    match subject:\n        case \"foo\":\n            return True\n        case _:\n            return False\n\n\nassert matches_str_first(StringStrFirst(\"foo\"))\n# do not want :(\nassert matches_str(StringStrFirst(\"foo\"))\n\nassert matches_match_args(StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"))\n# yay!\nassert not matches_str(StringMatchArgs(\"foo\"))\n```\n</details>\n\nI believe the only code that would break would be people who depended on having models not match themselves, which... well, [someone's always going to use emacs as a space heater](https://xkcd.com/1172/).\n@Kodiologist I view `(match (String \"foo\") (String \"foo\") 'pass  _ 'fail)` as a bug, so I agree with @KevinMGranger that this is a bugfix rather than a breaking change. I would find it highly surprising if anyone were relying on the current behavior, even if unintentionally.\n\n@KevinMGranger I suggest using the property-based accessor rather than setting a field, to minimize the chance of any sort of de-sync happening.\n\n---\n\nAnyhoodle, the reason why the various examples in this issue do/n't work is that `str` (and the other bulit-in types listed in the `match` docs) can be thought of as having something like `__match_args__ = ('(self)',)` (not actually a valid `__match_args__` but it gives the gist).\n\nSince `String` inherits from `str`, it also inherits this same behavior. When doing a case comparison then, Python compares the switch object's match fields to the tuple of args from the case pattern. For `String`, that effectively becomes `(String(\"foo\").(self),) == (\"foo\")`, which is why it fails.\n\n@Kodiologist's `class C` has a quirky definition of `__eq__` that ends up making the match cases work (it's comparing a field access on the left-hand side to the entire object on the right). Since `C` inherits the `str` class's \"compare self\" behavior, the match case is comparing `C(\"foo\")` itself vs the first subpattern `\"foo\"` from the case statement.\n```\nC(\"foo\") ==? \"foo\"\n=> C(\"foo\").a ==? \"foo\"\n=> \"foo\" == \"foo\"\n```\nHowever, if the `__eq__` method is changed to a more standard implementation\n```\ndef __eq__(self, other):\n    return isinstance(other, C) and self.a == other.a\n```\nthen the match cases fail, since (correctly) `C(\"foo\") != \"foo\"`.\nOkay, let's change this and advertise it as a bug fix. @KevinMGranger Create a pull request at your leisure.\n> I suggest using the property-based accessor rather than setting a field, to minimize the chance of any sort of de-sync happening.\n\n@scauligi what do you mean by \"de-sync\"? As in the field gets out of sync with the instance?\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/416529392f47d94adceb3776ad1b6bde186bad3c", "https://github.com/hylang/hy/commit/b38683e3b9b4d21a0619e20773900fc0dde79968"], "created_at": "2026-04-14T21:28:18Z"}
